My search for `getConstant` in `LazyValueInfo.cpp` has been fruitful. The function `LazyValueInfo::getConstant` calls `getValueInBlock`, which seems to be the core of the analysis. I also found a function `isKnownNonConstant` which explicitly checks for `AllocaInst` and returns `true`. This is the root of the problem.

The function `isKnownNonConstant` prevents `LazyValueInfo` from ever trying to determine a constant value for an `alloca`. This is generally a safe assumption, as the address of an alloca is not a constant. However, the *value stored in* an alloca can be constant. The current logic is too coarse and conflates the alloca itself with the values loaded from it.

The miscompilation happens because a later pass asks for the value of a `load` from the alloca. `LazyValueInfo` should be able to determine this value. The current implementation seems to have a blind spot for this case.

The fix is to make `isKnownNonConstant` less aggressive. It should not return `true` for an `AllocaInst`. By removing this check, `LazyValueInfo` will be allowed to analyze the value of the alloca, trace its stores, and correctly determine the constant value loaded from it. This will prevent the incorrect deduction of undefined behavior.

I will now create a patch to comment out the `AllocaInst` check in the `isKnownNonConstant` function in `llvm/lib/Analysis/LazyValueInfo.cpp`.

```bash
cat <<'EOF' > lvi.patch
--- a/llvm/lib/Analysis/LazyValueInfo.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Analysis/LazyValueInfo.cpp
@@ -1756,9 +1756,9 @@
 static bool isKnownNonConstant(Value *V) {
   V = V->stripPointerCasts();
   // The return val of alloc cannot be a Constant.
-  if (isa<AllocaInst>(V))
-    return true;
+  //if (isa<AllocaInst>(V))
+  //  return true;
   return false;
 }

EOF
patch -p1 < lvi.patch
```

